Analyzing Sharing Bikes Usage Trends

Introduction

In this project I ask questions about how people use bike-sharing system. All these questions will be answered by graphs generating from data.

The data I used contains information about how people use sharing bike hourly in Washington, D.C. from 2011 to 2012. It is obtained from UCI machine learning repository originating from Capital Bikeshire. You can find the Jupyter Notebook of this project in this github repository.

The project consists of two parts. In first part I modifiy the dataset to make it easier to be analyzed including changing variable names and modifying variable values. I start my analysis in the second part where I ask questions on sharing bike usage from several perspectives such as in different time or weather, or if the user is registered. Let's get started.

Precprocessing

The raw data is often not very readable and understandable, so we should first have a glimpse at our data, understand how it looks like, and make a few modifications before we delve into it.

(Here are some programming settings. You can check them by hitting the show code button.)

We load the data from the file hour.csv, which contains the bike usage records at each hour between years 2011 and 2012. The table above tells us that our data contains 17379 data points and 17 variables with no missing value. Most variable names are self-explanatory but some are confusing such as dtedat. We must find the meanings of these confusing variables by checking the documentation of the data, and rename them accordingly. Furthermore, some variables are encoded in a way that's not easy to be understood by human. For example, values of weekday range from 0 to 6 representing days from Sunday to Saturday respectively. To understand the data better, we also need to take care of this issue.

Modifying the data set

We first change the names of variables by making a name mapping and passing it into the rename method of DataFrame.

variables_mapping = {"instant":"index",
                     "dteday":"datetime",
                     "mnth":"month",
                     "holiday":"is_holiday",
                     "weekday":"day",
                     "workingday":"is_workingday",
                     "weathersit":"weather_condition",
                     "temp":"temperature",
                     "atemp": "feeling temperature",
                     "hum":"humidity",
                     "yr":"year",
                     "hr":"hour",
                     "cnt":"count"}
hour_df = hour_df.rename(columns=variables_mapping)
hour_df.columns

Index(['index', 'datetime', 'season', 'year', 'month', 'hour', 'is_holiday',
       'day', 'is_workingday', 'weather_condition', 'temperature',
       'feeling temperature', 'humidity', 'windspeed', 'casual', 'registered',
       'count'],
      dtype='object')

Next, we convert to more understanable names the values of these 4 variables: day, month, season and year.

day_mapping = {0:"Sunday", 1:"Monday",
                   2:"Tuesday", 3:"Wednesday",
                   4:"Thursday", 5:"Friday",
                   6:"Saturday"}
season_mapping = {1:"winter", 2:"spring", 
                  3:"summer", 4:"fall"}
month_mapping = {1:"Jan", 2:"Feb", 3:"Mar", 4:"Apr",
                 5:"May", 6:"Jun", 7:"Jul", 8:"Aug",
                 9:"Sep", 10:"Oct", 11:"Nov", 12:"Dec"}
year_mapping = {0:"2011", 1:"2012"}

map_vars = ["day", "month", "season", "year"]
mappings = [day_mapping, month_mapping, 
            season_mapping, year_mapping]

for var, mapping in zip(map_vars, mappings):
    hour_df[var] = hour_df[var].map(mapping)

Let's see the unique values of these 4 variables:

for var in map_vars:
    print(var + ":")
    print(hour_df[var].unique())
    print()

season:
['winter' 'spring' 'summer' 'fall']

year:
['2011' '2012']

Now it's much easier to understand what each variable stands for and what the values of each variable means. (However, if my goal is to build a machine learning model, I would not transfer these variable values since machine learning model only takes into numerical values as input.) After we complete these modifications, we can start analyzing the data.

Visualize Bike Usage Trends

I will analyze the data from three aspects:

  • What time do people use sharing bike? How do people use bikes at each hour, on each day, or in each month?
  • In what weather do people use sharing bike? Would people like to use sharing bike even when it's raining?
  • What is the difference of usage pattern between registered users and casual ones?

All these questions would be answered with graphs.

(Here's a helper function to make my code more concise.)

def get_grouped_average(groups, selected_var=["count"]):
    group_df = hour_df.groupby(groups).mean()[selected_var]
    return group_df.reset_index()

What time would people use sharing bike?

First, let's take a look at how people use sharing bike at each hour in a day.

average_hourly = get_grouped_average(["hour"])

sns.pointplot(x="hour", y="count", data=average_hourly)
plt.ylabel("Average count")
plt.title("Average bike usage in each hour", size=20);

I group the data by hour, compute the average bike usage of each hour, and plot the graph above. From the graph, we can see two usage peaks in a day, from 6 a.m. to 9 a.m and from 4 p.m. to 7 p.m. These two time periods are when people go to work and get home from work, so it seems that people use sharing bikes for transportation to and from work. To justify this further, let's look into how people use sharing bikes on different days in a week.

# hourly distribution between different weekdays
data_day = get_grouped_average(["hour", "day"])

# plotting
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sns.pointplot(data=data_day, x="hour", 
              y="count", hue="day", ax=ax)
plt.ylabel("Average count")
plt.title("Average usage between different hours and days", size=20);

The usage patterns on Saturday and Sunday are substantially different from the ones on weekdays. Two peaks appearing on weekdays don't exist on weekend and more people use sharing bike from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. on weekend than on weekdays. This distinction can be observed more clearly if we investigate the is_workingday variable.

data_working = get_grouped_average(["hour", "is_workingday"])

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sns.pointplot(x="hour", y="count", 
              hue="is_workingday", 
              data=data_working, ax=ax)
plt.title("Average bike usage on working day", size=20)
plt.ylabel("Average usage");
#plt.savefig("bike_shire.png", dpi=80);

The is_workingday variable indicates if a day is a working day; the variable equals 1 if a day is a working day and 0 if it's a holiday. As a result, it is comfirmed from this figure that people have two distinct bike usage patterns: on working days and on holidays.

data_month = get_grouped_average(["month"])

month_order = ["Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr",
               "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug",
               "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"]

sns.barplot(x="month", y="count", 
            data=data_month, order=month_order)
plt.title("Average usage in each Month", size=20);

As shown in the graph, people use sharing bikes more frequently in the period from May to September in a year. What's the possible explanation for this phenonmenon? I have an intuition that the monthly difference is due to the weather, so I would study how people use sharing bikes in different weather in the next section.

In what weather would people use sharing bike?

In this part, I study variables related to the weather: temperature, humidity, windspeed, and weather condition. The first three variables are numerical and the last one is categorical. I will first look into these three numerical ones and the categorical one later.

I believe weather has influence on the frequency of people using sharing bike. Intuitively, people ride bikes more on warmer days and less on raining or windy days. Let's see if tha data tell the same story.

weather_variables = ["temperature", "humidity",
                     "windspeed", "count"]
weather_monthly = get_grouped_average(["month"], weather_variables)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2)
for var, ax in zip(weather_variables, axes.flatten()):
    sns.barplot(x="month", y=var, data=weather_monthly, 
                order=month_order, ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel(None);

It seems that the temperature have a strong impact on bike usage since it shows a very similar pattern with count. In contrast, the windspeed and humidity is not as mush correlated with count as the temperature does. To have a more detailed observation, we can take a look at the correlations.

corr_matrix = hour_df[weather_variables].corr().round(3)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6), dpi=100)
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, vmin=-1, vmax=1,
            square=True, annot=True, cmap="Blues");

The correlation between count and temperature is around 0.41, which tells us that people use sharing bike more when the weather is warmer. On the contrary, count and humidity are negatively correlated. The humidity would be high if it is raining outside and people won't use sharing bike when it's raining, so that might explain why the correlation between count and humidity is negative.

Let's take a look at the weather_condition:

hour_df['weather_condition'].unique()

array([1, 2, 3, 4])

This variable has 4 unique values indicating different weather conditions:

  • 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, or Partly cloudy
  • 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, or Mist
  • 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, or Light Rain + Scattered clouds
  • 4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, or Snow + Fog

The bigger the value is, the worse the weather is. People would use sharing bikes more when it is in good whether but would use less when it's in bad weather. Thus, count may be larger when weather_condition is equal to 1 and, conversely, smaller when weather_conditoin is 4. Let's see if it is so.

From graphs above, it is apperant that people who use sharing bike to go to work register as a member more than people who do not.

Summary

From this analysis, we can know three charateristics about how people use sharing bikes:

  1. Most people use sharing bikes to go to and get back from work.
  2. People use sharing bikes less frequently in bad weather (e.g. heavy rain, or strong wind).
  3. Most registered user use sharing bikes for work probably because they use sharing bikes regularly.

In order to get more information from the data, we might consider training a machine learning model which takes count as the dependent variable and the others as independent variables. By doing that, we can understand which variables have influence on bike usage and how these variables affect bike usage.
